Illicit Drug Trafficking''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stopthedrugwar.org/chronicle/192/chinakillings.shtml |title=China Celebrates UN Anti-Drug Day With 59 Executions |publisher=Stopthedrugwar.org |accessdate=2011-02-17}}</ref> The government does not make precise records public, however Amnesty International estimates that around 500 people are executed there each year for drug offenses{{citation needed|date=August 2013}}. Those executed have typically been convicted of smuggling or trafficking in anything from cannabis to methamphetamine. |- |United States |Never imposed |While current US federal law allows for the death penalty for those who have extraordinary amounts of the drug (60,000 kilograms or 60,000 plants) or are part of a continuing criminal enterprise in smuggling contraband which nets over $20 million, the [[United States Supreme Court]] has held that no crimes other than [[murder]] and [[treason]] can constitutionally carry a death sentence; however, ''[[Kennedy v. Louisiana]]'' left open the possibility of capital punishment for crimes against the state (e.g., treason, espionage, drug kingpin activity) regardless of whether or not death actually occurred. (''[[Coker v. Georgia]]'' and ''[[Kennedy v. Louisiana]]'') |}<!-- deleted Taiwan section should be verified by another Chinese speaker |- |Taiwan. |Available |Death penalty is possible for drug offenses under Taiwanese law, but only for the creation, smuggling, and vending of "Class 1 Drugs,".<ref>http://law.moj.gov.tw/Scripts/Query4A.asp?FullDoc=all&Fcode=C0000008</ref> Cannabis is a "Class 2 Drug," the creation, smuggling, and vending of which can be punishable by life sentences or any sentence of more than 7 years, as well as a maximum fine of NT$70,000.-->
