'''Sir Thomas Alston, 5th Baronet''' (c. 1724 – 18 July 1774) was an English [[Baronet]] and [[Member of Parliament]].<ref name=Namier>[[Lewis Namier|Namier]] ''et al.'', ''The House of Commons 1754-1790'', Vol. 3, p.18</ref>

Thomas Alston was the eldest son of [[Sir Rowland Alston, 4th Baronet]] of [[Odell, Bedfordshire]].<ref name=Namier/><ref>Venn, ''[[Alumni Cantabrigienses]]'' seems confused, making him the second son of a Sir Rowland, Bart., and also succeed 'his brother Rowland' as Baronet in 1759.</ref> He was admitted at [[Queens' College, Cambridge]] in 1740.<ref name=Venn>{{acad|id= ALSN740T|name=Alston, Thomas}}</ref> From 1747 to 1761 he was MP for [[Bedfordshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Bedfordshire]]. In 1750 he married Catherine Davie Bovey, but separated from her by mutual consent two years later. Confined for a while to a [[Psychiatric hospital|madhouse]], he was nevertheless re-elected to Parliament unopposed in 1754. [[Horace Walpole]] reported a sorry appearance in the [[House of Commons of Great Britain|House of Commons]] in November 1755: "Poor Alston was mad, and spoke ten times to order."<ref name=Namier/>

On 2 January 1759 he succeeded his father as 5th [[Alston baronets|Baronet]]. He did not stand for Parliament in 1761.
Alston died 18 July 1774, leaving his property ([[Odell Castle]]) to his housekeeper Margaret Lee, through whom it eventually made its way to his illegitimate son Thomas.<ref name=Namier/> He was buried at Odell.<ref name=Venn/>

